<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Document</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/style.css">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://stackpath.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.5.0/css/bootstrap.min.css"
        integrity="sha384-9aIt2nRpC12Uk9gS9baDl411NQApFmC26EwAOH8WgZl5MYYxFfc+NcPb1dKGj7Sk" crossorigin="anonymous">


</head>

<body class="page">
    
    <!-- show informatin of entry.   Bootstrap website -->
    <div class="info">
        <div class="card" style="max-width: 20rem;">
            <div class="card-header">
                <p> Name: <%=balance.PatientName %></p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <div class="card-title">
                    <p>Date: <%=balance.TestDate%></p>
                    <p>Therapist: <%=balance.Therapist %></p>
                </div>
                <div class="card-text"> 
                    <!-- https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.1/layout/grid/ -->
                    <p>Balance Score:
                        <%= balance.score + balance.score1 + balance.score2 + balance.score3 + balance.score4 + balance.score5 + balance.score6 + balance.score7 + balance.score8 + balance.score9 %>
                    </p>
                    <p>Gait Score:
                        <%=balance.score10 + balance.score11 + balance.score12 + balance.score13 + balance.score14 + balance.score15 + balance.score16 + balance.score17 + balance.score18 + balance.score19 %>
                    </p>
                    <p>Total Score:
                        <%= balance.score + balance.score1 + balance.score2 + balance.score3 + balance.score4 + balance.score5 + balance.score6 + balance.score7 + balance.score8 + balance.score9  + balance.score10 + balance.score11 + balance.score12 + balance.score13 + balance.score14 + balance.score15 + balance.score16 + balance.score17 + balance.score18 + balance.score19%>
                    </p>
                    <form action="/assessment/<%=balance.id%>/edit" method="GET">
                        <input type="submit" value="Edit"/>
                        </form>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- info from bootstrap website https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.1/layout/grid/-->
    <div class="row no-gutter">
        <div class="col-md-3">Tinetti Score</div>
        <div class="col-md-3"">Fall Risk Interpretation</div>
        <div class=" w-100"></div>
        <div class="col-md-3"">Below 19</div>
        <div class=" col-md-3"">Highly Fall Risk</div>
        <div class="w-100"></div>

        <div class="col-md-3"">19-23</div>
        <div class=" col-md-3"">Moderate Fall Risk</div>
        <div class="w-100"></div>
        <div class="col-md-3"">Above 23</div>
        <div class=" col-md-3"">Low Fall Risk</div>
    </div>
    <div class="container">References
        <p>1) Tinetti ME, Williams TF, Mayewski R. (1986) <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3953620">Fall risk index for elderly patients based on number of chronic disabilities.</a> Am J Med; 80(3):429-34.</p>
        
        <p>2) Mancini M, Horak FB. (2010)<a href= "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3033730/"> The relevance of clinical balance assessment tools to differentiate balance deficits.</a> Eur J Phys Rehabil Med; 46(2): 239–248.</p>
        
        <p>3) Kopke S, Meyer G. (2006)<a href="https://www.chemie.uni-hamburg.de/igtw/Gesundheit/images/pdf/Koepke.pdf"> The Tinetti test, Babylon in geriatric assessment.</a> Z Gerontol Geriat 39:288–291</p>
        
        <p>4) Lin MR, Hwang HF, Hu MH, Wu HD, Wang YW, Huang FC. (2004)<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15271124">Psychometric comparisons of the timed up and go, one-leg stand, functional reach, and Tinetti balance measures in community-dwelling older people.</a> J Am Geriatr Soc; 52(8):1343-8.</p>
        
        <p>5) Mitchell KD, Newton RA. (2006) <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19260186"> Performance-oriented mobility assessment (POMA) balance score indicates need for assistive device.</a> Disabil Rehabil Assist Technol; 1(3):183-9.</p>
    </div>

</body>

</html>